                <div class="main">
                    <p>A binary number is a number expressed in the base-2 numeral system or binary numeral system, a method of mathematical expression which uses only two symbols: typically "0" (zero) and "1" (one).</p>
					<p><span style="color:green;"><b>Binary counting</b></span></p>
					<p>Binary counting follows the same procedure as decimal counting, except that only the two symbols 0 and 1 are available. Thus, after a digit reaches 1 in binary, an increment resets it to 0 but also causes an increment of the next digit to the left. Overview of binar numebrs representing numbers 0-12 in decimal system is presented in table below.</p>
					<table class="t1" style="margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;">
						<tr class="t1">
							<td class="t1 tableheader" ><b>Decimal numebrs</b></td >
							<td class="t1 tableheader" >&nbsp&nbsp&nbsp<b>Binary numbers</b></td >
						</tr>
						<tr class="t1">
							<td class="t1">0</td >
							<td class="t1">0</td >
						</tr>
						<tr class="t1">
							<td class="t1">1</td >
							<td class="t1">1</td >
						</tr>
